So why record a video
of your Android app?

00:00:33.020 --> 00:00:34.260
Good question.

00:00:34.260 --> 00:00:36.500
A video is an effective way
to demonstrate your app.

00:00:36.500 --> 00:00:39.140
And it gives users a quick
way to see how your app works

00:00:39.140 --> 00:00:41.720
and what it can do
before they download it.

00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:44.480
So it's a great
promotional tool.

00:00:44.480 --> 00:00:47.060
Creating a video that explains
how to use advanced features

00:00:47.060 --> 00:00:50.521
or correct common mistakes is
also a great use of app videos.

00:00:50.521 --> 00:00:52.270
Is there a question
about your application

00:00:52.270 --> 00:00:54.000
you get asked over and over?

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:57.810
Record a video to show
your users how it's done.

00:00:57.810 --> 00:01:00.110
So what do you need to use
the screen record feature?

00:01:00.110 --> 00:01:02.790
Well, you need a device
running Android KitKat,

00:01:02.790 --> 00:01:04.750
such as the Nexus 5.

00:01:04.750 --> 00:01:06.760
You also need a computer
with the Android Debug

00:01:06.760 --> 00:01:08.200
Bridge installed.

00:01:08.200 --> 00:01:10.820
If you have an Android software
development kit installed

00:01:10.820 --> 00:01:14.240
on your machine, then
you already have ADB.

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:16.370
Finally, you'll need
a micro USB cable

00:01:16.370 --> 00:01:19.490
to connect the computer
to your device.

00:01:19.490 --> 00:01:21.500
As I mentioned, you
don't need a video camera

00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:22.710
to use screen record.

00:01:22.710 --> 00:01:25.670
However, this feature
does not record audio.

00:01:25.670 --> 00:01:27.560
So if you want to
narrate your video,

00:01:27.560 --> 00:01:30.480
you need to use something to
record your voice as you demo.

00:01:30.480 --> 00:01:32.680
I recommend using a
second Android device

00:01:32.680 --> 00:01:34.520
with an app that does
high-definition voice

00:01:34.520 --> 00:01:36.690
recording.

00:01:36.690 --> 00:01:38.370
Here are the steps
to record a video.

00:01:38.370 --> 00:01:40.890
First, connect your USB
cable from your computer

00:01:40.890 --> 00:01:42.187
to your device.

00:01:42.187 --> 00:01:43.770
Then make sure it's
working by running

00:01:43.770 --> 00:01:48.320
a test command,
such as ADB Devices.

00:01:48.320 --> 00:01:51.020
Type the screen record command
to start recording, and then

00:01:51.020 --> 00:01:53.270
perform your demo on the device.

00:01:53.270 --> 00:01:55.070
If you're doing
narration of your demo,

00:01:55.070 --> 00:01:58.194
don't forget to turn
on your voice recorder.

00:01:58.194 --> 00:02:00.360
When you're done with your
demo, press the Control C

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:01.890
to end the recording.

00:02:01.890 --> 00:02:03.990
Finally, download
the recorded video

00:02:03.990 --> 00:02:07.280
to your computer using
the pull command.

